<div class="np-wrap">

  <div class="np-intro">
    <h2>Name Wordmark — Sans-serif Options</h2>
    <p><strong>Decision: ALL-CAPS.</strong> Both the design director and business director agree caps is right (your nav/headings are already an all-caps system) — and both <strong>cut Syne</strong>: wide faces collapse in caps. Recommended treatment below, then an all-caps comparison strip, then the full library for reference.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ============ CLEVER VS LAZY (UNBOUNDED) ============ -->
  <div class="np-band">
    <h3>"Clever" vs "lazy" — same brand font, two disciplines</h3>
    <p>Your real site chrome (logo + nav + name) mocked up two ways with Unbounded. Top: blanket it on <em>everything</em>. Bottom: Unbounded owns the name only, Lato keeps the UI. Watch the nav links especially — a wide rounded display face goes muddy and eats horizontal space at 13px.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="mock">
    <div class="mock-label bad">✕ Unbounded everywhere — reads lazy / mushy</div>
    <div class="mock-header">
      <img class="mock-logo" src="/uploads/2024/11/AshleyPimenta_Logo-2024.png" alt="AP">
      <nav class="mock-nav nav-unb"><a>Work</a><a>Photography</a><a>About</a></nav>
    </div>
    <div class="mock-hero">
      <h1 class="mh-name"><span class="l1">Ashley M.</span><span class="l2">Bettencourt-Pimenta</span></h1>
      <p class="mh-tag-unb">Graphic &amp; Digital Designer &nbsp;|&nbsp; Brand &middot; Campaign &middot; Digital &middot; Print</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mock">
    <div class="mock-label good">✓ Unbounded on the name only — reads intentional</div>
    <div class="mock-header">
      <img class="mock-logo" src="/uploads/2024/11/AshleyPimenta_Logo-2024.png" alt="AP">
      <nav class="mock-nav nav-lato"><a>Work</a><a>Photography</a><a>About</a></nav>
    </div>
    <div class="mock-hero">
      <h1 class="mh-name"><span class="l1">Ashley M.</span><span class="l2">Bettencourt-Pimenta</span></h1>
      <p class="mh-tag-lato">Graphic &amp; Digital Designer &nbsp;|&nbsp; Brand &middot; Campaign &middot; Digital &middot; Print</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ============ RECOMMENDED ============ -->
  <div class="np-rec">
    <p class="rec-flag">★ Recommended — both experts converge</p>
    <h1 class="rec-name">
      <span class="rec-l1">Ashley M.</span>
      <span class="rec-l2">Bettencourt-Pimenta</span>
    </h1>
    <p class="rec-desc">Graphic &amp; Digital Designer &nbsp;|&nbsp; Brand &middot; Campaign &middot; Digital &middot; Print</p>
    <p class="rec-note">Big Shoulders Display · 600 · UPPERCASE · +0.07em · two-line flush-left stack, line 2 ≈ 65% of line 1</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ============ HONORING THE BRAND FONT (UNBOUNDED) ============ -->
  <div class="np-band">
    <h3>Honoring the brand font — Unbounded</h3>
    <p>Unbounded is a Bettencourt Studios brand font, so it's worth seeing. The director's view: a brand font is permission, not obligation — it sprawls on the full 28-char name, but it <em>sings</em> on a short element. Three ways to play it, below.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Director's compromise: split lockup -->
  <div class="lockup brand">
    <span class="lock-tag"><em>★</em> Director's compromise — split lockup (brand honored + reads senior)</span>
    <h1 class="lk lk-split">
      <span class="s1">Ashley</span>
      <span class="s2">Bettencourt-Pimenta</span>
    </h1>
    <p class="lock-note">"ASHLEY" in Unbounded 500 (the brand font, where wide rounded sings) &nbsp;·&nbsp; "BETTENCOURT-PIMENTA" in Big Shoulders Display 600 (built for the long caps line)</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Brand-pure: all Unbounded -->
  <div class="lockup">
    <span class="lock-tag">Brand-pure — all Unbounded (the "doesn't embarrass itself" spec)</span>
    <h1 class="lk lk-uall">
      <span class="u1">Ashley M.</span>
      <span class="u2">Bettencourt-Pimenta</span>
    </h1>
    <p class="lock-note">Unbounded · 500 · UPPERCASE · +0.01em · two lines, line 2 ≈ 58% · note how wide the surname runs even at the smaller size</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ============ ALL-CAPS COMPARISON ============ -->
  <div class="np-band">
    <h3>All-caps, head to head</h3>
    <p>The top contenders set in caps at one size, so you can compare honestly now that caps is decided. Note the last one.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="caps-strip">
    <div class="cap-item"><span class="lbl">★ Big Shoulders Display — the pick</span><p class="cap-name opt-bigshould">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</p></div>
    <div class="cap-item"><span class="lbl">Oswald — fallback</span><p class="cap-name opt-oswald">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</p></div>
    <div class="cap-item"><span class="lbl">Bebas Neue — poster classic</span><p class="cap-name opt-bebas">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</p></div>
    <div class="cap-item"><span class="lbl">League Gothic — timeless gothic</span><p class="cap-name opt-league">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</p></div>
    <div class="cap-item"><span class="lbl">Inter — business director's neutral lean</span><p class="cap-name opt-inter">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</p></div>
    <div class="cap-item"><span class="lbl">Syne — <em>both experts cut it · see how wide+caps sprawls</em></span><p class="cap-name opt-syne2">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</p></div>
  </div>

  <!-- CURRENT -->
  <div class="np-card">
    <div class="np-tag">
      <span class="np-num">NOW</span>
      <span class="np-fontname">Source Serif Pro</span>
      <span class="np-spec">800 · Uppercase · -0.02em</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="np-name opt-current">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</h1>
    <p class="np-desc">Graphic &amp; Digital Designer &nbsp;|&nbsp; Brand &middot; Campaign &middot; Digital &middot; Print</p>
    <p class="np-why">What ships today — a serif, all-caps. The director wants to move off this to a sans for contrast with the mark.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- 1 SHIP -->
  <div class="np-card ship">
    <div class="np-tag">
      <span class="np-num win">01 · SHIP</span>
      <span class="np-fontname">Space Grotesk</span>
      <span class="np-spec">700 · UPPERCASE · -0.01em</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="np-name opt-space">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</h1>
    <p class="np-desc">Graphic &amp; Digital Designer &nbsp;|&nbsp; Brand &middot; Campaign &middot; Digital &middot; Print</p>
    <p class="np-why">Mechanical, slightly quirky grotesk — cold enough to contrast the ink-blob mark, but its angled terminals and distinctive G/a keep it from feeling corporate-dead. Best friction-vs-mark balance. <strong>The director's pick to ship.</strong></p>
  </div>

  <!-- 2 -->
  <div class="np-card">
    <div class="np-tag">
      <span class="np-num">02</span>
      <span class="np-fontname">Inter</span>
      <span class="np-spec">800 · UPPERCASE · -0.02em</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="np-name opt-inter">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</h1>
    <p class="np-desc">Graphic &amp; Digital Designer &nbsp;|&nbsp; Brand &middot; Campaign &middot; Digital &middot; Print</p>
    <p class="np-why">The neutral default of good product design — zero personality, maximum craft, pure foil to the mark. Risk: so neutral it can read "system font," a touch anonymous for a graphic designer's own name.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- 3 -->
  <div class="np-card">
    <div class="np-tag">
      <span class="np-num">03</span>
      <span class="np-fontname">IBM Plex Sans</span>
      <span class="np-spec">700 · UPPERCASE · -0.01em</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="np-name opt-plex">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</h1>
    <p class="np-desc">Graphic &amp; Digital Designer &nbsp;|&nbsp; Brand &middot; Campaign &middot; Digital &middot; Print</p>
    <p class="np-why">Engineered, humanist-grotesque, a touch of warmth in the curves. Reads beautifully at length. Loses to Space Grotesk only because it's softer, so the contrast with the mark is less electric.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- 4 -->
  <div class="np-card">
    <div class="np-tag">
      <span class="np-num">04</span>
      <span class="np-fontname">Jost</span>
      <span class="np-spec">700 · UPPERCASE · +0.005em</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="np-name opt-jost">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</h1>
    <p class="np-desc">Graphic &amp; Digital Designer &nbsp;|&nbsp; Brand &middot; Campaign &middot; Digital &middot; Print</p>
    <p class="np-why">Geometric Futura-revival. Elegant, but its perfect circles start to <em>echo</em> the round blobby mark instead of opposing it — closest to the wrong strategy. Fallback only.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ============ WIDER NET ============ -->

  <div class="np-band">
    <h3>Band B · Neutral grotesk alternates</h3>
    <p>Same "go quiet" thesis as the director's four — more cold, engineered grotesks if you like the strategy but not those exact faces.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="np-card">
    <div class="np-tag">
      <span class="np-num">05</span>
      <span class="np-fontname">Archivo</span>
      <span class="np-spec">800 · UPPERCASE · -0.01em</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="np-name opt-archivo">Ashley M. Bettencourt-Pimenta</h1>
    <p class="np-desc">Graphic &amp; Digital Designer &nbsp;|&nbsp; Brand &middot; Campaign &middot; Digital &middot; Print</p>
    <p class="np-why">Grotesque built for headlines — slightly narrow, editorial, a hair of grit. Holds the long name tighter than Inter without going cold-dead.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="np-card">
    <div class="np-tag">
      <span class="np-num">06</span>
      <span class="np-fontname">Manrope</span>
      <span class="np-spec">800 · UPPERCASE · -0.02em</span>
